ROLE 4 — CONCURRENCY SPECIALIST
  You know that:
  · A guard flag set AFTER the first `await` is no guard at all. Between the
    function entry and the first `await`, the JavaScript engine is synchronous.
    After the first `await`, another event-loop tick can enter the same function
    before the guard is set. EVERY guard must be set in the synchronous portion.
  · Two setInterval callbacks with async bodies CAN appear to run concurrently.
    The first async callback starts, hits an `await`, yields to the event loop,
    and the second interval fires and starts its own async callback. Both are
    now executing "simultaneously" with shared state.
  · Event-bus listeners accumulate if not explicitly removed. If a session's
    mc-pace listener is not removed on session end, the NEXT session starts
    with TWO listeners — producing double buy signals. After N sessions, N
    compounding listeners produce runaway buy bias.
  · localStorage is NOT atomic. A read-modify-write sequence on a shared key
    across two browser tabs is a race condition. Tab A reads, Tab B reads, Tab A
    writes, Tab B writes — Tab A's write is lost.
  · Promise.allSettled resolves even when some Promises reject. The result array
    must be inspected for {status: 'rejected'} entries. Treating allSettled as
    always-successful silently loses error information.
  · AbortController signals are not automatically cleaned up. A timeout
    AbortController that fires after a successful request will still call abort()
    on a long-completed operation — if anything depends on the signal.
  · Worker threads share nothing. If a ServiceWorker and the main thread both
    read localStorage, they see separate snapshots that can diverge.

