╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  COMPREHENSIVE AUDIT CHECKLIST — APPLY TO EVERY FILE, EVERY LINE             ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

━━━ SECTION 1: NUMERIC CORRECTNESS ━━━

  □ Every || vs ?? on numeric fields where 0 is a valid value
  □ Every parseInt — does it specify radix 10? Is the result NaN-guarded?
    Is it clamped to a valid range?
  □ Every parseFloat — NaN guard present? Clamped?
  □ Every Math.floor / Math.round / Math.ceil — correct choice for the domain?
    (floor for truncating lamports, round for display values)
  □ Every percentage computation: direction correct? (/ 100 or × 100?)
    Denominator zero-guarded?
  □ Every SOL ↔ lamport conversion: × 1_000_000_000 (integer) or BigInt?
    Never using 1e9 in float arithmetic for financial values?
    Never applying the conversion twice (double-multiply or double-divide)?
  □ Every floating-point comparison for financial equality
    (2.1 × 3 ≠ 6.3 in IEEE 754; use integer lamports instead)
  □ Every toFixed(N) result — is it passed to an API as a string or as a number?
    If the API expects a number and receives a string, behavior is undefined.
  □ Every bitwise operation on values > 2^31 - 1 (lamport values are often > 2B)
    Bitwise ops in JavaScript coerce to Int32, wrapping large values.
  □ Every accumulation of floating-point SOL values — should this be integer
    lamport accumulation instead?
  □ Integer overflow in lamport arithmetic — SOL amounts × 1e9 can exceed
    Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER for large balances. Use BigInt where needed.
  □ Negative lamport values — can any balance computation produce a negative
    lamport count? What is the behavior?
  □ Division before multiplication vs multiplication before division —
    order matters for integer truncation. Always multiply first.

━━━ SECTION 2: ASYNC AND CONCURRENCY ━━━

  □ Every setInterval callback that is async — is the returned Promise caught?
    setInterval(async () => { ... }) discards the Promise silently.
  □ Every async function called fire-and-forget — does it have .catch()?
  □ Every in-flight guard flag — is it set BEFORE the first await, or after?
    A flag set after the first await provides zero protection.
  □ Every shared mutable state accessed across await boundaries — can it be
    modified by a concurrent call between the read and the write?
  □ Every retry loop — exponential backoff? Maximum retry count? Can it infinite-loop?
  □ Every Promise.allSettled — are rejected entries (status:'rejected') handled?
  □ Every AbortController — is the timeout cleared on success? Does the abort
    signal affect anything after the operation completes?
  □ Every setTimeout ID — stored and clearTimeout() called on early exit?
  □ Every setInterval ID — stored and clearInterval() called when session ends?
  □ Every event-bus listener — is it removed when the session that registered it ends?
  □ Every recursive async function — is there a termination condition that is
    guaranteed to be reached in finite time?
  □ Every parallel wallet operation (Promise.allSettled over wallets) — is the
    wallet array captured by value or by reference? If it's mutated mid-await,
    the Promise already sent will use the old value.
  □ Every visibility change / focus event handler — debounced? Rate-limited?
    Two rapid focus events can start two trading engine sessions.
  □ Every cross-tab interaction via localStorage — localStorage.setItem and
    getItem are not atomic across tabs. Document every key that two tabs might
    write simultaneously, and identify the worst-case outcome.
  □ Zombie timers: any timer that should be cleared when the session ends but
    continues firing in the background, consuming CPU and producing phantom events.

━━━ SECTION 3: SCOPE, LIFETIME, AND CLOSURE ━━━

  □ Every `try { const x = ...}` — is x referenced after the closing brace?
    (const/let are block-scoped to the enclosing {})
  □ Every variable captured in a closure that is used after an await — could
    the outer scope have changed the value between capture and use?
  □ Every loop variable captured in a callback — is it the correct iteration
    value (via const) or the final loop value (via var)?
  □ Module-level state: is it reset between sessions? If a module-level Set or
    Map grows per session, it becomes a memory leak.
  □ Session objects: when a session ends (stop() or trigger), are all references
    to its state objects released? Can garbage collection reclaim them?
  □ Event listeners that stack: if init() is called twice, are listeners doubled?
    Is there a teardown path that removes all listeners before re-adding?
  □ chartData, tokenPollIntervals, holders, _pollInflight — do these grow
    without bound? Are they cleaned up when a token card is removed?
  □ Blob URLs created for image previews — are they ever revoked with
    URL.revokeObjectURL()? Unreleased Blob URLs hold entire File objects in
    memory indefinitely.
  □ localStorage keys: are old keys cleaned up? Does the namespace prevent
    collisions with other applications on the same origin?

━━━ SECTION 4: DATA INTEGRITY AND PERSISTENCE ━━━

  □ Every storage read that expects an array — Array.isArray() guard present?
  □ Every storage read — try/catch around JSON.parse? Safe default in catch?
  □ Every storage write — try/catch to handle QuotaExceededError?
  □ Corrupted wallet records (null address, null privateKey, wrong data type)
    — does the trading engine filter these before starting the loop?
  □ Deployment records missing required fields — does every read of every
    field have a safe default for records created before that field existed?
  □ baseMC / mcFloor / allTargetsHit — are all three persisted to storage
    immediately when set? Are all three restored with safe defaults on resume?
  □ launchTime / id mismatch — is the deadline base computed correctly for
    records that have one but not the other?
  □ exitPercentage NaN or out-of-range stored in old records — is it clamped
    at EVERY read, not just at write time?
  □ solPerWallet = 0 in a resume record — is it treated as "use the floor value"
    or as "zero SOL per wallet" (which would make every trade fail)?
  □ logoPath / bannerPath containing blob: URLs — are they stripped on resume
    (blob: URLs are invalid after page reload)?
  □ Stale cache race: when _launchesCache is invalidated, can an in-flight
    fetch IIFE overwrite the fresh data with stale data?
  □ All localStorage keys correctly namespaced — does any call to _storageSet
    or _storageGet pass a key that already starts with 'sas:' (double-prefix)?
  □ Deployment status forward-only: is there any code path that moves status
    BACKWARD (e.g., from 'completed' back to 'active')?
    The only valid exception is 'selling' → 'active' on cold reload.

━━━ SECTION 5: SECURITY AND INJECTION ━━━

  □ Every innerHTML / insertAdjacentHTML assignment — all user-controlled values
    (token names, symbols, addresses) passed through an esc() sanitizer?
  □ Every CSS attribute selector built with user data — CSS.escape() applied?
    Specifically: any [data-mint="..."] selector where mint comes from storage.
  □ Every URL built with user data — properly encoded? No javascript: scheme?
  □ Every console.log — could it print a private key, seed phrase, or full
    balance? Even partial key material is a security risk.
  □ CSP: does it allow all domains the code actually fetches?
    Does it block any domain the code needs?
    Are wss:// entries present for all RPC WebSocket connections?
  □ SRI hash: is it the correct sha384 for the exact CDN file version being
    loaded? Wrong hash = Web3.js silently not loaded = all transactions fail.
  □ Permissions-Policy header: correct scope for clipboard-write?
  □ Private key: is it EVER logged, included in error messages, passed in a URL,
    included in any event payload, or serialized to any non-local destination?
  □ openExternal / window.open: are all URLs validated for safe schemes
    (https only) before being opened?
  □ DOM clobbering: do any IDs in index.html shadow global properties or
    API functions that the code depends on?
  □ localStorage poisoning: does the deployments array read validate its
    contents (Array.isArray, record shape check) before trusting them?
  □ npm package audit: does any installed package have a published CVE? Does
    any package have unnecessarily broad access to file system, network, or
    environment variables?
  □ HTTPS enforcement: does the deployment serve all assets over HTTPS with
    HSTS header? HTTP allows cleartext private key exposure via clipboard API.

━━━ SECTION 6: PERFORMANCE AND SCALABILITY ━━━

  □ Every loop over wallets × anything — is it O(N) or O(N²)?
    At 5000 wallets, O(N²) produces 25 million iterations — catastrophic.
  □ Every getLaunches() / getCachedLaunches() call — through the cache, or
    a fresh localStorage read on every poll tick?
    At 1 poll/second with 50 tokens, uncached reads = 50 localStorage reads/second.
  □ Every querySelector inside a hot loop — can it be hoisted to a Map lookup?
    DOM queries are O(N) over the DOM tree.
  □ chartData growth — capped at MAX_CHART_POINTS? Cleared when token card removed?
  □ _pollInflight — uses `delete key` (removes entry) or `key = false` (accumulates
    dead entries forever)?
  □ Balance checks — batched via Promise.allSettled, not serial awaits?
    Serial awaits at 1 RPC call per wallet × 5000 wallets × 500ms latency = 41 minutes
    per sweep scan. That's longer than the confirmation buffer.
  □ Event listeners registered with { passive: true } where they don't call
    preventDefault? Passive listeners skip the thread-blocking check.
  □ Any redundant _safeRedistribute calls within the same cycle —
    should fire at most once per cycle, not once per low-balance wallet.
  □ Canvas chart re-render — debounced on resize? On every trade event?
    Without debounce, a high-frequency trading session re-renders the chart
    multiple times per second.
  □ JSON.stringify on large deployment arrays for localStorage write —
    is this happening on every poll tick? Could it be throttled?

━━━ SECTION 7: LOGIC AND CORRECTNESS ━━━

  □ Syntax errors and typos in identifiers (wrong variable names, wrong
    function names, wrong event channel strings)
  □ Incorrect operator precedence (||  vs ?? vs && vs ternary nesting)
  □ Off-by-one errors in loops, slice/splice, index math
  □ Wrong comparison operator (== vs ===, < vs <=, > vs >=)
  □ Dead code that shadows live logic (an if branch that can never be true,
    a catch block that handles an error that can never occur)
  □ Functions defined but never called / called but never defined
  □ Wrong event bus channel names — a typo in the emit string means the
    listener never fires, with no error
  □ Incorrect sort comparator — Array.sort with Math.random() as comparator
    produces biased shuffles that cluster certain values
  □ Hash space vs window size mismatches in anti-repetition buffers
    (verify: window < hash space for ALL four buffers)
  □ Trigger conditions that can fire before baseMC is established
    (baseMC = 0 → threshold = 0 → any organic MC > 0 triggers immediately)
  □ Timestamp unit mixing: some values in seconds, some in milliseconds,
    some in Solana slots — conversion must be explicit everywhere

━━━ SECTION 8: STATE MACHINE COMPLETENESS ━━━

  For each state machine, document:
    · All valid states
    · All valid transitions between states
    · All invalid transitions (and what prevents them)
    · What happens if the process restarts in each state
    · What happens if two transitions are attempted simultaneously

  □ Deployment status: null → active → selling → completed
    Can status jump from active to completed (skipping selling)? Should it?
    Can completed → active happen? Only by user action? No code path?
    Can selling → selling happen (double execution attempt)?

  □ TradingEngine session: not-started → running → triggerFired → stopped
    Can start() be called when already running?
    Can fireTrigger() fire twice for the same mint?
    Can stop() leave the session in a state where restart is blocked?

  □ RealMarketMonitor session: mirrors TradingEngine.
    Are RMM and TE always stopped and started together?
    Can one be running while the other is stopped? What breaks?

  □ UI launch flow: idle → launching → success | failure
    Can isLaunching get stuck true? Is EVERY failure path in a finally{}?
    Does the launch button re-enable on every failure path, including:
    - IPFS failure?
    - RPC timeout?
    - Bundle funding partial failure?
    - Token create rejection?
    - Any uncaught exception?

━━━ SECTION 9: BLOCKCHAIN-SPECIFIC CHECKS ━━━

  □ getBalance response shape: handles both {value: lamports} (new RPC) and
    bare lamports (legacy RPC) — extraction must check both shapes
  □ Transaction confirmation: does every send await confirmation (not just
    submission)? Spending unconfirmed balance is unreliable.
  □ Sell confirmation before sweep: sweep fires AFTER sell confirmation, not
    after sell submission. The 9-second buffer exists for this reason.
  □ Priority fee adequacy: are priority fees high enough to compete under
    validator congestion? A transaction that drops out of the queue returns
    success=false, but a transaction that times out may appear to fail but
    actually land in a future block.
  □ Transaction size: verify no single transaction exceeds 1232 bytes.
    This limit is not enforced client-side — violations fail at the validator.
  □ Blockhash TTL: is a fresh blockhash fetched on each retry attempt?
    A blockhash from a first attempt is expired by the third retry (~60s later).
  □ ATA creation cost: does wallet funding include the ~0.002039 SOL for
    Associated Token Account creation? A wallet funded without this allowance
    will fail its first buy with InsufficientFundsForFee.
  □ RPC Connection refresh: is the Connection object refreshed on endpoint
    rotation, or does a stale Connection continue using the old endpoint URL?
  □ pumpportal.fun API: does the code handle HTTP 429 (rate-limited) separately
    from generic errors? Rate-limited responses should not trigger full retry
    logic — they should wait and retry after the rate limit window.
  □ pump.fun bonding curve: is there logic to handle the token completing its
    bonding curve (complete: true)? Trading continues until trigger, but the
    price mechanism changes at this boundary.
  □ VersionedTransaction vs LegacyTransaction: does the signing path correctly
    handle both types? Signing a VersionedTransaction as Legacy produces a
    broken transaction silently.

━━━ SECTION 10: SERVICE WORKER SPECIFIC ━━━

  □ CACHE_VERSION: bumped in this pass? Does the activate handler delete ALL
    caches whose name doesn't match the new version?
  □ SW message handler: processes all known message types? Has a default
    fallback for unknown types (no throw)?
  □ SW fetch handler: guarded against chrome-extension://, moz-extension://,
    data:, and blob: scheme URLs? These crash the fetch handler.
  □ Navigation fallback: when the SW serves a navigation request from cache,
    is the cached index.html present? Missing fallback = blank screen offline.
  □ skipWaiting / clients.claim sequence: correct order? A SW that calls
    clients.claim before skipWaiting may control pages it didn't install for.
  □ Heartbeat sessions: cleaned up when empty? A SW heartbeat that keeps
    firing when all sessions are inactive wastes CPU on mobile.
  □ SW update flow: does the app notify the user when a new SW is waiting?
    Or does it silently continue with the old version until next cold start?

━━━ SECTION 11: DEPLOYMENT AND CONFIG ━━━

  □ vercel.json CSP headers match index.html meta CSP EXACTLY (same strings).
    A mismatch means the browser enforces the meta CSP for the first load
    and the Vercel CSP for subsequent loads — inconsistent behavior.
  □ All external domains in connect-src: pump.fun, pumpportal.fun,
    DexScreener API, all RPC endpoints, all IPFS gateways
  □ WebSocket endpoints in connect-src as wss:// (ws:// is different!)
  □ sw.js served with: no-cache (Cache-Control: no-cache),
    correct Content-Type (application/javascript), Service-Worker-Allowed header
  □ All six version strings consistent (see R9)
  □ HSTS header present for HTTPS enforcement
  □ X-Frame-Options or frame-ancestors CSP directive to prevent clickjacking
  □ X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff to prevent MIME type sniffing
  □ Referrer-Policy set appropriately (no private data in referrer headers)
  □ Permissions-Policy scoped correctly (clipboard-write: self only)

