║  Hunt for ALL instances of EACH pattern, not just one.                       ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

PATTERN A — OPERATOR COERCION  (|| vs ??)
  `expr || default` when expr can be 0 and 0 is a valid value.
  Seen in: exitPercentage (×4+), autoSellMultiplier (×2+), solPerWallet (×1+).
  Search: every `|| 100`, `|| 0.01`, `|| 20`, `|| 0.5`, `|| 24`, `|| 7500`.
  Also search: `= params.X || ` — every parameter destructure with fallback.
  Fix: use ?? for numeric fields where 0 is valid. Document every || that is
  intentional (treating 0 as falsy) with a comment explaining why.

PATTERN B — BLOCK-SCOPE TRAP  (try {} const)
  `const x` or `let x` declared inside `try {}` but referenced after the `}`.
  Seen in: `_allDeps` (r61-1), `_validInBatch` (r51-1).
  Search: every `try {` block. List every identifier declared inside. Check
  every reference to that identifier in the enclosing function scope.
  Fix: declare variables outside the try block, assign inside.

PATTERN C — CODE-IN-COMMENT  (// text \n actualCode)
  A literal backslash-n sequence in a single-line comment makes everything
  after `//` dead code, including the intended fix.
  Seen in: r68-1 (startTs never set), r68-2 (_sweepAttempted never declared).
  Search: every `//` comment line containing the literal characters \ and n
  adjacent to each other. If code follows that sequence, it is dead.
  Fix: extract the code, place it on its own line outside the comment.

PATTERN D — MISSED SISTER PATH  (fix in one path, not all)
  A root cause exists identically in multiple code paths but only one is fixed.
  Seen in: exitPercentage clamp (auto-trigger fixed, manual missed), launchTime||id
  (TE fixed, RMM missed), swept flag, onAutoSellFailed cache-clear.
  Search: for every fix applied in this pass, find ALL other code paths that
  call the same function or apply the same logic. Fix every path, not just one.

PATTERN E — UNREGISTERED FALLBACK  (anti-repetition buffer bypass)
  When the primary selection loop exhausts and falls to a fallback, the fallback
  value must be registered in the buffer. Unregistered fallbacks produce repeating
  parameter identical to the previous fallback on consecutive calls.
  Seen in: _tradeParams (r44-2), _uniqueBuyPct (r53-1), _uniqueSellPct (r53-1).
  Search: every function with a "safety fallback" comment or a final return
  after an exhausted loop. Does it push to the buffer before returning?

PATTERN F — STALE-WINDOW BUFFER SATURATION
  Anti-repetition buffer window ≥ hash space = permanent saturation after N
  unique values. Every subsequent call goes to fallback. Fallback behavior
  determines whether trades appear truly unique.
  Seen in: _recentDelayBuckets, _recentBuyPctBuckets, _recentSellPctBuckets, _recentParamHashes.
  Search: every circular buffer constant. Compute hash_space = (number of
  distinct possible values the hash function can produce). Verify window_size <
  hash_space by at least 10%.

PATTERN G — MISSING NULL GUARD ON EVENT PAYLOAD
  An event handler receives `d` from the bus and accesses `d.field` without
  checking `if (!d) return` first.
  Seen in: onAutoSellComplete (r66-2), onSolSwept (r64-1), onOrganicMcUpdate.
  Search: every `window.electronAPI?.onXxx?.(d => {` handler. Does it start
  with `if (!d) return`? Or at minimum `if (!d?.requiredField) return`?

PATTERN H — MISSING .catch() ON ASYNC FIRE-AND-FORGET
  An async function called without `await` and without `.catch()`. Also:
  `setInterval(async () => {...})` — the returned Promise is silently discarded.
  Seen in: _startPricePolling (r21-1), pollTokenData interval (r45-1).
  Search: every `setInterval(async`, every non-awaited call to an async function
  at the top level of any other function.

PATTERN I — CONNECTION OBJECT STALE AFTER ENDPOINT ROTATION
  A single `conn = _getConnection()` captured before a retry loop becomes stale
  if _rpcIdx rotates during the operation.
  Seen in: _fundWalletsReal (r25-2), _redistribute (r26-8).
  Search: any function that makes multiple batched RPC calls and captures a
  connection ONCE before the batch loop.

PATTERN J — BLOB URL NOT STRIPPED ON RESUME
  blob: URLs stored in logoPath/bannerPath become invalid after page reload.
  Truthy string but 404 request.
  Seen in: _resumeActive (r48-4).
  Search: every place a deployment record is read on resume. Are blob: URL
  fields detected (startsWith('blob:')) and cleared before use?

PATTERN K — DOUBLE-NAMESPACE STORAGE KEY  (sas:sas:key)
  `_storageSet('sas:keyname', ...)` produces key `sas:sas:keyname` — permanently
  orphaned, never read back.
  Seen in: boot() (resolved), but can recur on any future key addition.
  Search: every call to `_storageSet` or `_storageGet` where the key argument
  already starts with the prefix string.

PATTERN L — VERSION DRIFT BETWEEN DUAL EMIT SITES
  engine-version badge emitted in TWO places. One updated, other overwrites
  with stale data after every launch.
  Seen in: _launchTokenReal emit (r69-3 — features frozen at r64).
  Search: find BOTH emit('engine-version', ...) calls. Compare version strings
  and features[] arrays character by character.

PATTERN M — INCOMPLETE CACHE INVALIDATION ON STATE CHANGE
  When deployment record status changes, the renderer's _launchesCache must be
  invalidated AND refreshTokensView() called. Missing either leaves the card
  stuck in the wrong state for up to the TTL.
  Seen in: onAutoSellFailed (r69-1).
  Search: every code path that writes a deployment status change. Does the
  corresponding renderer handler invalidate cache AND call refreshTokensView()?

PATTERN N — BASEMAC NOT PERSISTED BEFORE FIRST TRIGGER CHECK
  If baseMC is latched in memory but not persisted to the deployment record
  before a page reload, the session resumes with baseMC = 0. The trigger
  threshold becomes 0 × multiplier = 0. The first poll tick triggers immediately.
  Search: every code path that sets baseMC. Does it immediately write the new
  value to the deployment record in localStorage?

PATTERN O — SELL TRIGGER USES FLOOR-CLAMPED MC INSTEAD OF RAW MC
  The trigger calculation must use `td.mc` (raw on-chain value) NOT `state.mc`
  (which may be floor-clamped). Using state.mc when allTargetsHit=true means
  the floor permanently inflates the trigger target, making it unreachable.
  Search: every code path in RMM._poll that reads the market cap for trigger
  comparison. Is it td.mc or state.mc?

PATTERN P — SWEEP FLAG SET FROM KEY EXISTENCE INSTEAD OF EXECUTION RESULT
  `swept: !!devKey` emits true even if the sweep was never attempted because
  devKP (keypair) failed to deserialize. Only `swept: _sweepAttempted` where
  _sweepAttempted is set inside the `if (devKP)` block is accurate.
  Search: every emit('auto-sell-complete', ...) call. Is swept computed from
  !!devKey/!!devKeyString or from an actual execution flag?

PATTERN Q — LASTTRADETS INITIALIZED TO 0 INSTEAD OF Date.now()-N
  lastTradeTs initialized to 0 causes the first poll tick to treat ALL historical
  trades as new — producing a massive false organic volume spike that triggers
  immediately on resume.
  Search: every RMM.start() or session initialization that sets lastTradeTs.
  It must be Date.now() - SOME_BUFFER (e.g., 5000ms), never 0.

PATTERN R — POLL TICK DEDUP COUNTER NOT RESET PER TICK
  A no-signature trade dedup counter that accumulates across ticks instead of
  resetting at the start of each tick produces incorrect organic volume counts.
  Search: the no-sig dedup counter reset logic. Where is it reset to 0?
  Is it before or after the trades are processed?

PATTERN S — BUDGET LEDGER NOT RE-INITIALIZED ON RESUME
  If BudgetLedger.init(totalSol) is not called before TradingEngine.start() on
  session resume, solPerWallet() returns the floor value (not the actual budget),
  and every trade uses the minimum amount regardless of configured budget.
  Search: the _resumeActive function. Does it call BudgetLedger.init() with the
  correct totalSol value before starting the trading engine?

PATTERN T — WALLETS NOT VALIDATED BEFORE TRADING LOOP
  Null address or null privateKey in the wallets array causes a TypeError
  mid-loop. The error is caught by the loop's try/catch, but the loop skips
  that wallet permanently — silently reducing effective cluster size.
  Search: TradingEngine.start() and every function that passes a wallets array
  to the loop. Is there a filter for valid wallet records before the loop?

PATTERN U — EVENT BUS CHANNEL NAME TYPO
  The event bus uses string keys. A one-character typo in the emit string means
  the listener never fires — no error, no warning, just silence.
  Search: every _bus.emit() and every _bus.on() call. Build a complete registry.
  Does every emit string have a corresponding on() with the EXACT same string?
  Use the Event Bus Channel Registry below as your reference.

PATTERN V — GETBALANCE RESPONSE SHAPE NOT NORMALIZED
  getBalance() returns {value: lamports} on some RPC nodes, bare lamports on
  legacy nodes. Code that always accesses .value fails on legacy nodes; code
  that treats the response as a number fails on new nodes.
  Search: every getBalance call. Does the result extraction handle both shapes?

PATTERN W — PRIORITY FEE INSUFFICIENT UNDER CONGESTION
  A fixed priority fee may be adequate under normal conditions but too low to
  compete when the Solana network is congested. A dropped transaction returns
  no error — it simply times out. Retry logic must handle this and may need
  to escalate priority fees on retry.
  Search: every setComputeUnitPrice call. Is the fee value static? Is there
  fee escalation on retry? Is the fee denominated correctly (micro-lamports)?

PATTERN X — ORGANIC VOLUME CALCULATION COUNTING BUNDLE WALLET TRADES
  If knownWallets is stale (e.g., after wallet regeneration mid-session), new
  bundle wallet addresses are not excluded from organic volume calculation.
  This inflates organic MC, potentially triggering the sell prematurely.
  Search: the knownWallets refresh rate. How many poll ticks between refreshes?
  Does it rebuild from CURRENT clusterAccounts, not a cached snapshot?

PATTERN Y — RECONCILIATION FAILURE: COMMITTED TRANSACTIONS NOT TRACKED
  A transaction that was submitted and confirmed on-chain but whose confirmation
  was not observed by the client (due to RPC timeout) will be retried — creating
  a double-spend. The retry mechanism must check on-chain state (getTransaction)
  before resubmitting.
  Search: every retry loop for buys and sells. Does it query the chain for the
  previous attempt's status before resubmitting?

PATTERN Z — MISSING FINALLY{} IN CRITICAL OPERATIONS
  A function that disables a button at the start and re-enables it only in the
  success path leaves the button permanently disabled if any exception is thrown.
  Any non-try/finally pattern is a latent permanent-disable bug.
  Search: every function that disables a button or sets an isLoading flag. Is
  the re-enable/reset in a finally{} block, not just in the success path?

PATTERN AA — STALE CLOSURE CAPTURING WALLET ARRAY
  The trading loop captures the wallets array at session start. If the user
  regenerates wallets while the session is running, the loop uses the old array.
  knownWallets must be rebuilt to exclude new wallets from organic volume, and
  the trading loop should detect the stale wallet map and refresh.
  Search: how does TradingEngine respond to mid-session wallet regeneration?
  Is there a notification mechanism? Does it rebuild its wallet references?

PATTERN AB — RATE LIMIT HANDLING CONFLATED WITH GENERIC ERROR HANDLING
  HTTP 429 from pumpportal.fun means "slow down" — backoff and retry.
  HTTP 500 means "server error" — retry with same parameters.
  HTTP 400 means "bad request" — retrying is pointless and wastes time.
  Conflating all non-2xx as generic retryable errors causes retry storms on 429
  and infinite loops on 400.
  Search: every API call error handler. Does it check the status code?
  Does it have different handling for 429 vs 5xx vs 4xx?

PATTERN AC — TIMESTAMP UNIT CONFUSION (ms vs s vs slots)
  JavaScript Date.now() returns milliseconds. Solana slot timestamps are in
  seconds. Some internal counters use slots as a proxy for time. Mixing these
  units produces incorrect elapsed time calculations and deadline errors.
  Search: every use of Date.now() in time comparisons. Every use of slot
  numbers as time proxies. Are all units consistent? Are conversions explicit?

PATTERN AD — MISSING GUARD ON DOUBLE-TAB OR DOUBLE-CLICK LAUNCH
  A rapid double-click on the Launch button can execute launchToken() twice.
  The first call may not have set the in-progress guard before the second click
  fires. This can create two competing launch sessions for the same token.
  Search: every button click handler for the Launch button. Is the in-progress
  guard set synchronously (before any await) in the click handler itself?

PATTERN AE — SWEEPING BEFORE ALL SELLS ARE CONFIRMED
  The sweep timer starts when sell TRANSACTIONS are submitted, not when they
  are confirmed. If the confirmation time exceeds the sweep buffer (9s), the
  sweep reads balances before sell proceeds are credited. The sweep transfers
  only what was in the wallet before the sell — losing the sell proceeds.
  Search: the timing relationship between executeSellAll and the sweep trigger.
  Is the 9s buffer measured from submission or from confirmation?
  Field evidence: at 7s confirmation times under congestion, a 6s buffer fails.
  The current 9s buffer exists for this reason. Do NOT reduce it.

PATTERN AF — VERSION STRING CHECK MISSING IN FORM STATE RESTORE
  If FORM_VERSION is bumped but the form state in localStorage is NOT cleared
  (because the version check passes without triggering StateManager re-init),
  old form values (including a stale exitPercentage or autoSellMultiplier from
  before a fix) will be restored into the form and then written back to new
  deployment records.
  Search: the StateManager version check. Does a version mismatch trigger a
  full storage clear of form-related keys? Does it re-initialize all defaults?

