╔══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╗
║  TEN DEEP-THINKING LENSES                                                    ║
║  Apply ALL TEN to every significant bug and every significant fix.           ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════╝

LENS 1 — THE STRANDED-FUNDS LENS
  "Could this bug cause SOL or tokens to be permanently unrecoverable,
  even if the user refreshes, retries, or waits?"
  Stranded-funds bugs are the highest severity because they have no recovery
  path that doesn't require manual on-chain intervention. Ask for EVERY
  transaction, EVERY sweep, EVERY sell, EVERY redistribution.

LENS 2 — THE SILENT-FAILURE LENS
  "Could this bug produce a wrong result with no error, no console log,
  and no visible sign to the user?"
  Silent failures are deadlier than crashes. A crash tells the user something
  went wrong. A silent failure lets them believe everything is fine while
  their position is open, their sweep returned nothing, or their SOL is
  draining into fees.

LENS 3 — THE WORST-CASE-RESUME LENS
  "What is the worst possible state this could be in after a page reload,
  tab crash, browser kill, or network loss at the worst possible moment?"
  For every piece of state: if the process died RIGHT HERE, what would
  _resumeActive find? Would it do the right thing, or would it make things worse?

LENS 4 — THE OLD-RECORD LENS
  "What happens if this code runs against a deployment record created 10
  versions ago, before this field existed?"
  Fields added in later releases are undefined in old records. Every read of
  any stored field needs a sane default, or it becomes the root cause of a
  class of bugs that is incredibly hard to reproduce in development but
  triggers reliably for users who have been using the app for months.

LENS 5 — THE CONCURRENT-ACTION LENS
  "What happens if two things happen simultaneously that the developer assumed
  would be sequential?"
  Examples: organic trigger fires + user clicks Sell Now simultaneously.
  Page becomes visible + trigger fires during the 2-second timer.
  Wallet regeneration during a recirculation pass.
  Two rapid launch clicks. Every shared guard must be set BEFORE the first await.

LENS 6 — THE ADVERSARIAL INPUT LENS
  "What is the worst input a hostile user (or a corrupted localStorage)
  could provide, and what happens when that input reaches every code path?"
  Negative percentages. Integer overflow values. NaN. Empty strings.
  HTML/JS injection in token names. Malformed private keys.
  Corrupted JSON in storage. Every code path must handle adversarial input.

LENS 7 — THE FINANCIAL PRECISION LENS
  "Is every computation that involves money done with sufficient precision
  and in the correct numeric type?"
  SOL has 9 decimal places of precision. JavaScript floats have 15–17 significant
  digits. At large balances, float arithmetic drifts. For any amount > 0.1 SOL,
  accumulation in float arithmetic can produce lamport-level errors.
  All financial arithmetic should use integer lamports.

LENS 8 — THE PROTOCOL CONTRACT LENS
  "Does this code respect every Solana/pump.fun protocol requirement,
  including ones that are not enforced client-side?"
  Transaction size limit. Blockhash TTL. Priority fee requirements.
  ATA creation costs. VersionedTransaction signing API. Confirmation timing.
  pumpportal.fun API rate limits. Bonding curve price impact.
  Any violation of these is a latent failure that will surface under
  production conditions even if tests pass.

LENS 9 — THE ENTROPY LENS
  "Does every randomized parameter have sufficient entropy to be unpredictable?"
  Anti-repetition buffers only guarantee distinctness within a window — they
  do not guarantee unpredictability. If Math.random() is used as the entropy
  source, and if the buffer hash function has poor distribution, consecutive
  trades may cluster in a narrow range that is identifiable by MEV bots.
  Verify that the hash distribution of all four buffers is approximately uniform
  across the entire hash space.

LENS 10 — THE TEMPORAL DEPENDENCY LENS
  "Does this code assume a specific ordering of asynchronous events that
  is not guaranteed by the JavaScript runtime?"
  Example: assuming that event A always fires before event B because A is
  emitted first in the code — but in a concurrent async context, B may
  process first due to microtask scheduling. Any code that depends on
  event ordering without explicit sequencing is a timing bug waiting to happen.

